JAUNDICE - INDIA: (JAMMU AND KASHMIR) CONTAMINATED WATER, REQUEST FOR
INFORMATION
*********************************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 22 Sep 2011
Source: Kashmir Dispatch [edited]
http://www.kashmirdispatch.com/headlines/22095991-two-infants-woman-die-due-to-diarrhoea-in-south-kashmir.htm


A local news agency reported on Thu 22 Sep 2011 that 3 people
including 2 infants have died while 13 people have been hospitalized
in south Kashmir's Shopian district due to an outbreak of jaundice. It
said that 2 pregnant women hailing from Karwadah in the district were
suffering from jaundice and were shifted to the SMHS hospital [in
Srinagar] today [22 Sep 2011]. Both women delivered, but the infants
did not survive and passed away minutes after being born.

Doctors at the hospital told the news agency that the infants died due
to jaundice. The news agency said that [one of the women] also passed
away after delivering her baby.

The agency quoted its correspondent in Shopian saying that many
patients were shifted to local hospitals in the districts, while 13
people were shifted to SK Institute of Medical Sciences in Soura,
Srinagar. The condition of 2 of the patients, it said, was critical.
Meanwhile, the department of Health has established a camp in the
area, the agency said.

In total 22 patients have been identified in the area and [on the
basis of their] the condition some have been referred to Srinagar
hospital, chief medical officer Dr Nazir Ahmad said. He admitted that
the risk of pregnant woman catching the disease was higher. Regarding
the death of the mother, he said, "Even though we don't have exact
details about her, she was said to be suffering from hepatitis during
her pregnancy."

People in the area have expressed anger against the Public Health
Engineering Department [PHE] for failing to provide a clean water
supply. The water tank constructed by the PHE has not been cleaned
[for a long time] and is not well kept, they alleged. Experts say that
the outbreak is primarily due to [consumption of] contaminated water.

--
