[Jaundice is caused by a build-up of bilirubin in the blood and
tissues of the body. Bilirubin is a waste product that is produced
when red blood cells break down. Jaundice can occur as a result of any
condition, problem, or underlying factor that disrupts the movement of
bilirubin from the blood to the liver and then out of the body.
Intra-hepatic jaundice occurs when damage to the liver disrupts the
liver's ability to process bilirubin. Causes of intra-hepatic jaundice
include: the viral hepatitis group of infections (hepatitis A,
hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and hepatitis E viruses), leptospirosis (a
bacterial infection that is spread by animals, particularly rodents
and is common in tropical areas), glandular fever (caused by the
Epstein-Barr virus), and over-exposure to substances such as alcohol,
paracetamol, phenolic compounds, etc, autoimmune disease, and certain
genetic conditions.

Perhaps hepatitis E virus infection is the most likely cause of the
outbreak in Shopian which is associated with an inadequately
maintained water supply. Such outbreaks have not been uncommon in
India in the past. Further information is awaited concerning the
investigation into the causation of this outbreak.

Shopian District is one of the districts of Jammu and Kashmir state,
India. Its headquarters are located at Shopian city. A map showing the
location of Shopian district can be accessed at
http://jammukashmirrealities.blogspot.com/2010/07/map-showing-boundaries-of-district_20.html.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of India can be seen at
http://healthmap.org/r/1hcH. - Mod.CP]
